<div class="status-box">
    <b>June 22, 2019 Update:</b> This is an archive version of the analysis of the North Houston Highway Improvement Project.
    Updated schematics were placed on the official web site in May 2019, and the most recent update of the analysis is <a href="@Url.Action("analysis")">here</a>.
    <div style="padding: 10px 0 2px 0;">Changes to the schematic in May 2019 were very minimal and did not affect any of the items listed here, so the information on this page remains valid.</div>
</div>

@*<div class="textblock">
        TxDOT’s recommendation for downtown freeways and Interstate 45 North is the most influential recommendation for Houston’s freeways since the 1950s.
    TxDOT and its partners deserve credit for a bold plan to fully modernize downtown Houston freeways and enhance mobility.
    However, review of the preliminary schematics reveals numerous points of concern which could compromise the ability of the new freeway system to meet current and future needs.
    </div>*@
@*<div style="color:red; font-weight: bold; padding-bottom: 10px;">UPDATE SEPT 28, 2015: TxDOT has recently posted updated schematics on the project web site. This analysis will be updated in early October.</div>*@

@*<div class="bold">Updates resulting from July 22 and September 4, 2015, meetings with TxDOT</div>*@


<div class="updateItem">
    Updated schematics for the project were placed online in May 2018. Changes in the May 2018 schematics were very minimal compared to the May 2017 schematics.
    @*For complete coverage of the May 2017 schematics including annotated PDF files, see the @Html.ActionLink("May 2017 analysis archive", "analysis_May_2017").*@
</div>

<div class="updateItem">
    @*Unfortunately, the May 2018 schematics included no changes at any of the locations of my items of concern. So as of May 2018 it appears that <span style="font-weight: bold">the design is final at the locations of my concerns, and the design weaknesses will be carried through to construction.</span>*@
    Unfortunately, the May 2018 schematics included no changes at any of the locations of my items of concern. However, a project representative informed me that adjustments to the design including some of these concerns are still possible in a future re-evaluation of the ROD (Record of Decision).
    As of January 2019, it appears that the ROD is going to be delayed and is no longer expected in early 2019. A re-evaluation would occur after the initial ROD is received but before construction begins. Depending on the section of the project, a re-evaluation could be soon after receipt of the ROD or years in the future.
</div>

<div class="updateItem">
    @*Since my concerns were submitted as official public comments, I trust that they were evaluated by project representatives. I can only assume that changes to address my concerns were not warranted, were technically infeasible or were not cost-effective.
        Nevertheless, I'm disappointed that there were no design improvements relating to any of my items of concern.*@
    Of course, I would be pleased to see some adjustments at any of the locations of concern before the project proceeds to construction. And I realize that changes in many or most locations may not be warranted, technically feasible or cost effective.

</div>

<div class="updateItem">
    Still, even with my remaining concerns, the project provides huge benefits to the downtown Houston freeway complex, so I continue to support the project and encourage TxDOT to proceed to construction as soon as possible.
</div>


